WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.160
Hi. Welcome to the Opportunities App. Opportunities is a new app for the Edovo platform that helps you view your potential release dates

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:10.720
and understand the definitions of different release types.

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:15.280
Before this app, the only way to see your release dates was to request a time comp sheet

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:21.600
or to wait to ask your COIII. And we know that can take days or even weeks, especially when staff

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:26.880
are busy. With Opportunities, that information is on your tablet anytime you want to check it.

00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:32.080
The app shows release dates that you currently get through a time comp or by asking a COIII.

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:36.960
explanations of different release types, their requirements and conditions in plain language.

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:42.560
This application is for general and supplemental purposes only. It is not intended to be substituted

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:46.320
for the official record of this information. Now, let's demo the app.

00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:52.400
This is what you'll see once you're in the portal. The general structure is a homepage

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:57.120
that shows your release dates, an about page that discusses what the Opportunities app is

00:00:57.120 --> 00:01:01.680
and an explainer page with information about what the dates mean and links on the homepage

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:06.160
that take you to specific parts of that page. The first thing you'll see at the top of the

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:10.880
homepage is this light-gray banner. This banner shows the date the information was last changed.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:15.760
You may also see this section that will only apply to a certain group of people.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:20.480
This is a section that notes someone may be eligible for DPR. This will only be shown to

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:25.920
people who have drug possession or use charges and therefore could qualify for a 70% release

00:01:25.920 --> 00:01:31.920
instead of an 85% one. If you click on the Learn More button in the DPR banner, you'll be taken to

00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:37.200
a page titled "You may qualify for earlier release through Drug Program Release (DPR). What does that

00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:43.040
mean?" The purpose of this page is to help people who only have those drug possession or use charges

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:48.560
understand how to qualify for DPR, mainly by emphasizing the need to complete a major program.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:53.200
If we return to the homepage, you'll see a section called Your Important Dates.

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:56.960
This section is meant to explain some of the dates you'll see and where they come from.

00:01:57.520 --> 00:02:03.440
We know sentence dates can be confusing. You might hear terms like ERCD or SED thrown around

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:09.280
and not be sure which one actually applies to you or what the difference is. We've heard people say

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:14.000
they've been given different answers by different people about what a date meant. That's exactly why

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.720
each date here comes with a plain English summary, so you're not left guessing or relying on second-

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:24.160
hand information from the yard. You may see several different possible release dates depending on your

00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:29.360
sentence. Not everybody will have all of the possible dates. The app shows only the dates that

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:35.040
apply to you. You will see the sentence name, acronym, date, amount of time from the date,

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:41.040
and summary in plain English. If you click on the "Learn more about XYZ", you'll be taken to an

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:45.760
explainer page with information about what the date means. Each link directly corresponds to a

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:51.520
specific explanation on a larger about page. When you arrive on the explainer page, you will notice

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:56.960
two sections at the top. One titled My Release Dates, which provides explainer information for

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:01.760
the dates that are applicable to you, in addition to the All Release Types section that provides

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:07.360
information on all release types that are possible. The information for each date is organized around

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:11.840
common questions that you may have in order to understand how to qualify for that release type,

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:16.880
and what it would mean for you. When navigating across each section, you can tap on individual

00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:22.160
questions to see their answers, or you can easily collapse or expand the information by clicking

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:28.000
on the Close All Content and Open All Content button in the top right corner of each section.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:33.760
Ultimately, this app itself is designed to be very simple. Just three pages, one that shows

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:38.560
your dates and the demo video, an about page that provides information about what the Opportunities

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:43.520
app is, and another containing descriptions about those dates. It's similar to the information that

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:48.240
will be contained in a time comp sheet, but just always available through the tablet.

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:52.960
A few additional important notes. A banner at the top of your tablet screen will tell you when the

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:58.400
data has been last updated. The app refreshes every day, but you may not notice any changes

00:03:58.400 --> 00:04:03.200
unless your release date has changed for some reason — for example, if you get a disciplinary

00:04:03.200 --> 00:04:07.920
infraction and lose dates, or qualify for early release through a transition program.

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:13.760
One thing we heard during our pilot of this app is people said that being able to see their dates

00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:18.480
regularly helped them stay focused on their goals. If you complete a transition program and qualify

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:23.280
for early release, you'll be able to see that change reflected here. And if you lose days from a

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:28.240
disciplinary infraction, you'll see that too. Some people told us that was actually a helpful

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:33.520
reminder of what's at stake. This tool will only live on your tablet. It will only show your own

00:04:33.520 --> 00:04:38.880
information, not others'. It will not show information about your crime. This app uses the

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:44.080
real info from the time comp office. It doesn't make up its own dates. And if you have questions

00:04:44.080 --> 00:04:48.880
about your sentence structure, you will need to speak with your COIII. If you have questions about

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:52.960
the app, here's who you should start by talking with. If you have questions about your sentence

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:58.160
structure, your COIII or time computation unit is the best answer. If you have questions about

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:03.840
your release dates, your COIII or time computation unit is the best answer. If you're having issues

00:05:03.840 --> 00:05:09.840
with your tablet or lost your login information, mail and property are the best answer. Finally,

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:15.040
knowing your dates isn't just about counting down. People preparing for release use these dates to plan:

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:20.160
coordinating with family about housing, timing job searches, and signing up for the right programs

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:24.720
in the right order. The earlier you have a clear picture of your timeline, the more time you have

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:30.000
to prepare for a successful return home. Thank you.
